<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-665-974  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 665 974.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 12 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Court rules states can regulate Bell gateways.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     State GovernmentBell Regional Holding CompaniesSubsidiary CompaniesGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COURT RULES STATES CAN REGULATE BELL GATEWAYS SAN FRANCISCO, CALIFORNIA,U.S.A., 1990 JUN 6 (NB) -- States have the right to regulate local phonecompanies and deny the Bell companies the right to combine their regulatedand non- regulated industries.andP;  The decision, by a 3-judge panel of the U.S.andO;Court of Appeals in San Francisco, will likely be appealed to the U.S.andO;Supreme Court.andP;  For now, however, it overrules the 1985 decision of theFederal Communications Commission which preempted  state regulation ofcomputerized phone services.andM;State regulators now may require the nation's Bell operating companies to setup independent subsidiaries to provide specialized computer services that usethe same telephone lines as regular consumer phone service.andP;  All the Bellcompanies, however, have unregulated subsidiaries, most of which are involvedin cellular telephone and international operations.andM;The decision could prove especially significant for the Bell Gateway trials,which link consumers to information providers through local networks.andO;Presently, the Bell companies must have separate gateway operations in eachcity where they do the business.andP;  US West has a gateway in Omaha, BellSouthone in Atlanta, Bell Atlantic has gateways in Philadelphia and Washington,D.C.andP;  while NYNEX has three -- in New York, Boston, and Burlington, Vermont.andO;The FCC wants to deregulate those operations, gaining control of the 1984Bell break-up from Judge Harold Greene in the process.andP;  The Appeals Courtdecision throws another monkey-wrench in those plans, and could move theBells to throw in the towel on their gateways, which are not believed to becommercially successful.andM;Dozens of the nation's leading computer and telecommunications companiesjoined in the lawsuit on the side of the FCC, including MCI, IBM, NYNEXTelephone Companies, ATandamp;T, and GTE Telephone Operating Companies.andP;  Joiningthe California PUC in their winning arguments were New York state and theMichigan Public Service Commission.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900608)</TEXT></DOC>